## Code of Conduct

### Our Pledge

We are committed to providing a welcoming and inspiring community for all. Please be respectful, constructive, and inclusive in all interactions.

### Expected Behavior
- Be professional and courteous
- Respect diverse opinions and backgrounds
- Give credit where credit is due
- Be patient and helpful
- Report inappropriate behavior

### Unacceptable Behavior
- Harassment or discrimination
- Abusive or disrespectful language
- Personal attacks
- Spam or unwanted promotion

---

## Getting Started

### Prerequisites
- Android Studio (Latest version)
- JDK 11 or higher
- Git
- Basic knowledge of Kotlin and Android development
- Firebase account

### Fork & Clone Repository

```bash
# 1. Fork the repository on GitHub
# Visit: https://github.com/yourusername/esports-tournament-manager
# Click "Fork" button

# 2. Clone your fork
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/esports-tournament-manager.git
cd esports-tournament-manager

# 3. Add upstream remote
git remote add upstream https://github.com/ORIGINAL_OWNER/esports-tournament-manager.git

# 4. Verify remotes
git remote -v
# Should show:
# origin    https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/esports-tournament-manager.git
# upstream  https://github.com/ORIGINAL_OWNER/esports-tournament-manager.git
```

### Setup Development Environment

```bash
# 1. Create and checkout feature branch
git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name

# 2. Configure your Firebase project
# Add google-services.json to app/ directory

# 3. Open in Android Studio
# File → Open → Select project directory

# 4. Build the project
./gradlew clean build

# 5. Run tests
./gradlew test
```

---

## Development Workflow

### 1. Identify Issues to Work On

```
a) Check GitHub Issues: https://github.com/yourusername/esports-tournament-manager/issues
b) Look for issues marked:
   - "good first issue" (for beginners)
   - "help wanted"
   - Your area of expertise
c) Comment on issue to express interest
d) Wait for maintainer approval before starting
```

### 2. Create Feature Branch

```bash
# Use descriptive branch names
git checkout -b feature/add-live-streaming
git checkout -b bugfix/fix-login-crash
git checkout -b docs/update-readme

# Branch naming convention:
# feature/description - for new features
# bugfix/description - for bug fixes
# docs/description - for documentation
# refactor/description - for code refactoring
# test/description - for test improvements
```

### 3. Make Changes

```bash
# Write code and commit regularly
git add .
git commit -m "Add feature X"

# Keep commits focused and meaningful
# Make small, logical commits
```

### 4. Sync with Upstream

```bash
# Before submitting PR, sync with upstream
git fetch upstream
git rebase upstream/main
# or
git merge upstream/main
```

### 5. Push to Your Fork

```bash
git push origin feature/your-feature-name
```

### 6. Create Pull Request

- Go to your fork on GitHub
- Click "Compare & pull request"
- Fill in the PR template
- Submit for review

---

## Coding Standards

### Kotlin Style Guide

#### Naming Conventions

```kotlin
// Classes: PascalCase
class AdminMainActivity : AppCompatActivity()
data class TournamentModel(val id: String, val title: String)

// Functions/Methods: camelCase
fun getTournaments() {}
fun createNewTournament() {}

// Variables: camelCase
val tournamentList = ArrayList<Tournament>()
var isLoading = false

// Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
companion object {
    const val DATABASE_URL = "https://..."
    const val TIMEOUT_SECONDS = 30
}

// Private members: prefix with underscore (optional)
private val _tournamentList = MutableLiveData<List<Tournament>>()
val tournamentList: LiveData<List<Tournament>> = _tournamentList
```

#### Code Structure

```kotlin
// Class organization:
class AdminMainActivity : AppCompatActivity() {
    
    // 1. Companion object
    companion object {
        private const val TAG = "AdminMainActivity"
    }
    
    // 2. Properties
    private val binding: ActivityAdminMainBinding by lazy {
        ActivityAdminMainBinding.inflate(layoutInflater)
    }
    private val db = FirebaseFirestore.getInstance()
    
    // 3. Lifecycle methods
    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        setContentView(binding.root)
    }
    
    // 4. Public methods
    fun loadTournaments() {
        // implementation
    }
    
    // 5. Private methods
    private fun setupListeners() {
        // implementation
    }
}
```

#### Comments and Documentation

```kotlin
/**
 * Loads all tournaments from Firestore database.
 * This function is called when the app starts.
 *
 * @return List of Tournament objects
 */
fun loadTournaments(): List<Tournament> {
    // Single line comment for brief explanation
    val tournaments = ArrayList<Tournament>()
    
    // Multiple lines for complex logic
    // This checks if the tournament is active
    // before adding it to the list
    for (tournament in allTournaments) {
        if (tournament.status == "ACTIVE") {
            tournaments.add(tournament)
        }
    }
    
    return tournaments
}
```

#### Best Practices

```kotlin
// ✓ Good: Use val instead of var
val result = calculateScore()

// ✓ Good: Use when instead of if-else for multiple conditions
when (role) {
    "admin" -> showAdminPanel()
    "player" -> showPlayerDashboard()
    "spectator" -> showLiveMatches()
}

// ✓ Good: Use scope functions
Tournament().apply {
    title = "Tournament Name"
    prizePool = 1000000
    entryFee = 500
}.also { saveTournament(it) }

// ✗ Avoid: Null pointer exceptions
val name = user?.name ?: "Unknown"

// ✓ Good: Use safe calls and let
user?.let { safeUser ->
    loadUserProfile(safeUser.id)
}
```

